":"Cruden Bay, Aberdeenshire, Schotland","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Scotland":"Schotland"},"en":{"1415–1500":"1415–1500","1420–1486":"1420–1486","1420–1503":"1420–1503","1440–Female":"1440–Deceased","1450–1520":"1450–1520","1386–1460":"1386–1460","1390–1463":"1390–1463","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1390":"1390","1415":"1415","1503":"1503","1500":"1500","1444":"1444","1520":"1520","1486":"1486","1420":"1420","Abt 1440":"about 1440","1463":"1463","1386":"1386","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Market Harborough, Leicestershire, England":"Market Harborough, Leicestershire, England","Cruden, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Cruden Bay, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","England":"England, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Watson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Irish: patronymic meaning ‘son of <i>Wat</i>’, a pet form of   Walter   that was particularly common in Scotland and northern England. See   Watt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Walter","meanings":["English (of Norman origin), German, Dutch, Polish, Swedish, and Danish: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This personal name was introduced into England both in the reign of Edward the Confessor and by the Normans (in the forms <i>Walt(i)er</i>, <i>Waut(i)er</i>). After the Norman Conquest it soon became one of the most popular personal names in Britain. Compare   Walther  .","Germanized or Americanized form of Czech, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian <b>Valter</b> and Czech <b>Valtr</b>: from the personal name <i>Valter</i>, <i>Valtr</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Hurst","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form, first recorded in the 15th century, of the Old Saxon name <i>Horsa</i> ‘horse’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Hurst Watson was born in 1415, in Cruden Bay, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, his father, John Watson, was 29 and his mother, Janet McDonald, was 25. He married Patricia Hale in 1444, in Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1500, in his hometown, at the age of 85."},"et":{"1415–1500":"1415–1500","1420–1486":"1420–1486","1420–1503":"1420–1503","1440–Female":"1440–Surnud","1450–1520":"1450–1520","1386–1460":"1386–1460","1390–1463":"1390–1463","1440":"1440","1450":"1450","1460":"1460","1390":"1390","1415":"1415","1503":"1503","1500":"1500","1444":"1444","1520":"1520","1486":"1486","1420":"1420","Abt 1440":"umbes 1440","1463":"1463","1386":"1386","Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Market Harborough, Leicestershire, England":"Market Harborough, Leicestershire, England","Cruden, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Cruden Bay, Aberdeenshire, Scotland","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland"},"fi":{"1415–1500":"1415–1500","1420–1486":"1420–1486","1420–1503":"1420–1503","1440–Female":"1440–Kuollut","1450–1520":"1450–1520","1386–1460":"1386–1460","1390–1463"